RegExp Quantifiers:

- Quantifiers define the numbers of characters or expressions to match.
    // Match at least one zero
    const pattern = /0+/;


#) JavaScript RexExp Quantifiers: Revised July 2025

        Code	    Description
    ---------------------------------------------------------
        x+	        Matches at least one x
        x*	        Matches zero or more occurrences of x
        x?	        Matches zero or one occurrences of x
        x{n}	    Matches n occurences of x
        x{n,m}	    Matches from n to m occurences of x
        x{n,}	    Matches n or more occurences of x


1️⃣ RegExp + Quantifier:
    - x+ matches matches at least one x.
    - eg: A global search for at least one "o":

        let text = "Hellooo World! Hello W3Schools!";
        const pattern = /o+/g;
        let result = text.match(pattern);
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // ooo,o,o,oo

2️⃣ RegExp * Quantifier:
    - x* matches zero or more occurrences of x.
    - eg: A global search for an "l", followed by zero or more "o" characters:

        let text = "Hellooo World! Hello W3Schools!"; 
        const pattern = /lo*/g;
        let result = text.match(pattern);
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // l,looo,l,l,lo,l

3️⃣ RegExp ? Quantifier:
    - x? matches zero or one occurrences of x.
    - eg: A global search for "1", followed by zero or one "0" characters:

        let text = "1, 100 or 1000?";
        const pattern = /10?/g;
        let result = text.match(pattern);
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // l,10,10

4️⃣ RegExp {n} Quantifier:
    - x{n} matches n occurences of x.
    - eg: A global search for a string that contains a sequence of four digits:

        let text = "100, 1000 or 10000?";
        const pattern = /\d{4}/g;
        let result = text.match(pattern);
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     //  1000,1000

5️⃣ RegExp {n,m} Quantifier:
    - x{n,m} matches from n to m occurences of x.
    - eg: A global search for a substring that contains a sequence of three to four digits:

        let text = "100, 1000 or 10000?";
        const pattern = /\d{3,4}/g; 
        let result = text.match(pattern);
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // 100,1000,1000

6️⃣ RegExp {n,} Quantifier:
    - x{n,} matches n or more occurences of x.
    - eg: A global search for a sequence of at least three digits:

        let text = "100, 1000 or 10000?";
        const pattern = /\d{3,}/g; 
        let result = text.match(pattern);
        document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = result;     // 100,1000,10000


#) Regular Expression Methods:
    - Regular Expression Search and Replace can be done with different methods.
    - These are the most common:

    1️⃣ String Methods
        
        Method	            Description
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
        match(regex)	    Returns an Array of results
        matchAll(regex)	    Returns an Iterator of results
        replace(regex)	    Returns a new String
        replaceAll(regex)	Returns a new String
        search(regex)	    Returns the index of the first match
        split(regex)	    Returns an Array of results
    
    2️⃣ RegExp Methods

        Method	            Description
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
        regex.exec()	    Returns an Iterator of results
        regex.test()	    Returns true or false